{"id":"1912.08328","submitter":"Yuval Wigderson","authors":"Jacob Fox, Sammy Luo, Yuval Wigderson","title":"Extremal and Ramsey results on graph blowups","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recently, Souza introduced blowup Ramsey numbers as a generalization of\nbipartite Ramsey numbers. For graphs $G$ and $H$, say\n$G\\overset{r}{\\longrightarrow} H$ if every $r$-edge-coloring of $G$ contains a\nmonochromatic copy of $H$. Let $H[t]$ denote the $t$-blowup of $H$. Then the\nblowup Ramsey number of $G,H,r,$ and $t$ is defined as the minimum $n$ such\nthat $G[n] \\overset{r}{\\longrightarrow} H[t]$. Souza proved upper and lower\nbounds on $n$ that are exponential in $t$, and conjectured that the exponential\nconstant does not depend on $G$. We prove that the dependence on $G$ in the\nexponential constant is indeed unnecessary, but conjecture that some dependence\non $G$ is unavoidable.\n  An important step in both Souza's proof and ours is a theorem of Nikiforov,\nwhich says that if a graph contains a constant fraction of the possible copies\nof $H$, then it contains a blowup of $H$ of logarithmic size. We also provide a\nnew proof of this theorem with a better quantitative dependence.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 18 Dec 2019 00:45:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 6 Apr 2020 21:26:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-08"}
